segments.text: Any important, any famous people through SCONA?
No.
Who were the, do you remember some of the speakers?
No, I just remember they were congressmen or senators, but I don't remember who they were.
Because somewhere about that time, Senator Albert Gore of Tennessee came, I remember that.
Could very well be.
about that time, and I remember he was very pleasant and personable and so forth.
I just attended the evening programs where they had speakers and things like that.
Did you become involved as a SCONA worker or anything?
No.
And you, would you and your buddies go over and hang out a little bit in the MSC?
Yes.
There wasn't a lot of time though.
The day was pretty well taken up.
And like you said earlier, you took a lot more hours.
And so you were in class a good deal today, or labs.
And the science courses you were taking, every one of them had a four-hour lab.
Guyen Hall, did you remember going to any movies or activities in Guyen Hall?
Yes.
Describe what went on during a movie when Aggies were in the audience in Guyen Hall.
Well, if there was any slight mention of sex or anything like that, they kind of would whoop and carry on like, you know, banjis and things like that.
Because they used to be, the campus theater used to have the Friday night groads, groad flex they were called.
Oh, I don't know what to describe that.
Well, there was a series of films that showed.
It was called Mr. Peepers, as I remember.
And just for all of these women wearing bikinis and other things like that.
I mean, nudity to the degree it's allowed today wasn't allowed.
And they were just walking around doing things.
And so you were going and watching, you know, skint, partially clad women.
And they were called the Grove Flex.
And it was, they were never officially announced.
It was just kind of word got out that Friday night at the campus theater was Grove Flex were going on.
And I remember old Schumann would stand out there.
He just took a dollar from everybody coming in the door, you know.
Were these late?
Oh yeah, they started like 11, 12 o'clock at night.
And it would be filled with an all-meal?
Oh yeah.
And what noises were made during the flicks?
Animals.
And lots of whooping and carrying on and stuff like that, yeah.
Did anybody take drinks in there?
Not that I'm not an alcoholic, not that I know of.
You probably wouldn't have got away with that.
They were going to sell you a Coke.
That was part of the reason for the movie is that you can sell popcorn, you know.
And let's see, religious activities.
Did you take part in any?
Yeah, at St. Mary's, you know, the...
Describe that, because we don't, I don't know much about what was the...

Well, you know, you were still in that age where you went to church every Sunday, and you'd go to church over there, and then, you know, maybe some involvement, once again, with the Newman Club, the Catholic student organization.
They would have some maybe social activities afterwards or dances, and like I said, that's where I met this girl from Houston who, she was a, you know, I came from a very large family with children,
There were seven boys and two girls in the family.
Her family was like seven girls and two boys.
And so it was, I don't know, that's... Was there a Sunday night event?
No.
When did Newman Club meet?
Well, maybe there were some evening things, yeah.
But I guess it was evening.
Yeah.
During the weekdays, could you go over there to kind of escape from the corps?
Well, I didn't.
You didn't?
Yeah.
There may have been some of that.
Was there a campus, a Catholic chaplain kind of somebody that you all would go to?
Occasionally, yeah, and he used to figure I would come around and visit people in the dorm room.
Oh, he would?
Well, the priest would, yeah.
Oh, really?
I didn't... Well, we're talking about, you know, six, seven thousand students at A&M in total, you know, graduate and everything, I think, probably not much more than that.
And, yeah, you know, if he became active in that, he would come by and occasionally somebody I know would organize
that the priest was coming over and we'd get together in a room and maybe he'd talk about things.
As far as you can recall, describe the A&M student body at that time in terms of attitude, economics, geographic background, ethnicity and so forth, religious attitudes and so forth.
Well, there are no blacks, a few Hispanics, very few, primarily Anglo, of course all male.
I think it was a pretty diverse group in a sense of economics.
There was a lot of, you know, some very wealthy kids and also some very, you know, poor kids as well, you know.
Where were they from geographically?
I think all over the state, even then.
Were there many out of staters, out of country?
Very few.
As I recall, there was one guy, Fish Yaskovic, from Yonkers, New York.
So we went out to one of these drinking in the woods one night.
I still remember Yaskovic got out of the car and he looked up and he says, Jesus Christ, you guys got a lot more stars in Texas than we do in New York.
Anyway, very few out of state students.
One kid, you know, he came to A&M not, he wanted to be a veteran, you know, and his family had been involved in a lot of horse racing in Delaware, I believe.
He was from Delaware.
And he came to A&M not knowing that it was all male.
Because he said, and he showed us, they sent him these brochures.
And they had pictures of women that was, of course, taking social events or summer school or some other time.
And he didn't know what he was getting into.
The basic attitudes of these students, liberal, conservative?
I don't know that, you know.
that there was that much politics discussed, quite frankly.
There was an anti-letting women in, and that sort of thing.
And the same sort of tunnel vision that even probably more so,
even a mild criticism would result in someone suggesting that Highway 6 ran both directions, you know, and if you don't like it, you can leave.
Of course, they were still saying that a lot when I came back on the faculty.
Were there any Jewish kids, you remember?
There may have been a few, but I'm not sure.
Basically, were, was everybody accepted
by and large, was it an inclusive or an exclusive group?
Well, I think it was inclusive.
I think it probably still is in the sense that Aggies pull together and that kind of thing.
I know we had one kid one time that went over to snook to the SPJST hall and got into a fight and was arrested.
He fought a local boy, so they arrested him, not the other guy that beat him up.
And so we had to go get him out of jail.

And I finally got, you know, found out where he was, and he said, well, you have to go see the J.P. And so he takes us down to the J.P.'s house, you know, and we have this hearing, and there's this light hanging from a bulb, and the damn thing is swinging back and forth.
The police officer explains what happened, you know, and the judge says, guilty, you know.
I mean, he doesn't even get a chance to get, this guy wants to get back to bed.
And anyway, so many dollars, and everybody pitches in.
Bails this guy out so he doesn't have to spend the night in jail.
Now did you guys on Saturdays go to Snoop to eat kolaches?
I didn't.
The bakery I don't think was there.
If it was, I didn't know about it.
I didn't know about it by then, if it was.
Later we would discover it, of course.
Yeah.
You know, there was this dance hall over there, and it was the SPJST, the thing.
And you would go over there and it was...
They had these bleachers along the sides of the thing.
And there would be these old Czech women sitting in there.
I guess they were sort of the chaperones.
And there might be some local girls that would come out and dance.
But they were watched very closely by these.
these elderly women.
And it was all, I call it the Winthorpe shuffle, but it was really the Texas two-step.
But in Wichita Falls we were just too damn sophisticated for that stuff, you know, and then doing that kind of dance.
We did the real dancing.
Anyway.
The other student organizations, how did you and your buddies feel about the singing cadets and the Aggie band and things like that?
What prestige?
I don't know.
I mean, everybody loved the band, you know.
They used to say, well, have a football team the band can be proud of someday.
And, of course, the Ross Volunteers were considered a really elite group that somebody got into that that, you know.
There was probably more competition for that then than there is now by ten times.
Was it a big deal to be a yell leader then?
Oh, yeah.
Sure.
What was the sublime student leadership role?
What do you mean by that?
If you could have had any student leadership position, what would have been the one that was most respected?
Oh, company commander.
Or corps commander, I presume.
Well, yeah, but the really big deal was the company commander, more so than I think it is today, that the guys that got to be company commanders were the kind of, at least within that group.
Now, going to corps staff was obviously a
a very prestigious thing to happen to you.
And of course, you got picked your junior year.
Corps staff was picked in the junior year.
Were you and your buddies aware of elected student body officers much?
Well, yeah.
You were marched over as a company and told how to vote.
Oh, really?
Oh, yeah.
Had voting machines that were the old lever.
Only time I've ever seen them except when I was in Maryland graduate school.
You went in and you were told how to vote and who to vote for.
I think they still do some of that.
But the student body president did not rank at all.
Oh, no.
Now, if you were a student body president, yeah, I guess that was an important position.
I don't mean to say it wasn't, but not as corps commander was God.
Were you aware in those days of any secret fraternities?
No.
There may have been some, but I wasn't aware of them.
So far, I've only had one person admit that he knew they existed.
Well, I literally don't know.
They may have.
But there's some others that I know were members that I've interviewed.
There's a yearbook in 32 or something that has the swastikas in the corner and Wayne Stark.
It goes way back before that.
What was this called?
The stickers, the swastikas.
And they discovered that.
You see, that was a Navajo symbol.
They discovered that long before the Nazi Party had.
Is that right?
Yeah.
I knew it was a novel symbol.
I think Mr. Evans was a sticker.
Is that right?
The two that I know of were the TTs, the something Texans.
Tough Texans.
True Texans.
True Texans.
True Texans, yeah.
And the swastikas.
And as far as I can determine, the only purpose they had at all was to see that one of their group was the corps commander and the head deal leader.
In other words, it was to get their little clique.
The local party.
Yeah, it was a political party.
And there was nothing ulterior or anything.
Now, Harrington, he cracks down on them.
Is that right?
Yeah, in the 50s, early 50s, late 40s, and kicks two or three out of school because they denied it.
Well, if there was any of that going on when I was a student, I was completely unaware.
But that's entirely possible, too.
Let's see.
There are no veterans coming back, so that's not an appropriate question for me to ask you.
You mentioned that summer job.
Did A&M help you get that veterinary?
No.
I'd worked for them when I was in high school originally.
And then after your second year, you have decided not to do veteran medicine, and you go back to Midwestern for your senior year?
Yeah, and then I had another year after that.
Because I really got way behind, you know.
Let's see, back to the community.
How often did you and your buddies go to Bryan?
Oh, very seldom.
Because you didn't do much shopping.
No.
And did you go down there to a movie?
Yeah, occasionally to the old Bryan Theater in downtown Bryan.
Was there any area of Bryan where supposedly something illicit or extreme went on?
If there was, I didn't know about it.
I've never heard any stories about gambling.
There was a place where they served family-style meals.
In fact, it was still going when I came back.
I forget the name.
A big old boarding house.
Yeah, that thing.
And they had lots of home-cooked stuff, everything fried or boiled, you know.
And you go down there and for, I don't know, $3 or $4, you could eat all you wanted.
I remember Linda and I, after we came back, I went there a couple of times.
It's still going.
I don't know what it is anymore.
What about J.E.
Lupo?
Did you meet him?
Mm-hmm.
Describe him and what kind of guy he was.
Well, I know I needed a slide rule because I couldn't get through all these math and problems and everything, and particularly the long division and the time necessary to finish the test.
And I'd learned how to use a slide reel in high school.
And so I went over there to buy one.
And I was looking at what he had.
And I didn't have enough money to get any of them.
And he said to me, what's wrong with that?
And I said, well, I just don't have that much money.
He said, well, how much can you pay?
And I told him, he said, sold.
And his daughter, who's a very good friend of mine now, her husband did his master's thesis under me and Artie.
She's bought the stores from her brother, and so I see her all the time.
She's really upset about all this off-street parking stuff in Northgate now and is down.
She lives in Austin, but she's here two or three days a week and has a house on Gilchrist just down from me.
So, you know, I told her that story one time, and she said, yeah, the dad did that a lot.
Did you ever hear anything negative about Lupo?
Well, I think they used to say, old Army Lou, he'll screw you.
But did you ever hear of him jipping anybody?
No.
I think it was just a catchy phrase.
And I heard him say a number of times that he had never loaned a snaggy money, that he didn't get it paid back.
And I've never heard anybody
else, just like you, that if they were broke and needed a book or a piece of equipment, he always helped them.
Pinky Downs.
I don't know that I knew Pinky when I was a student here.
When I came back, and maybe I did because I don't, but Pinky was still hanging around, the official greeter.
Describe him in that role.
What did he do and where and how?
Well, he hung around the MSC and greeted people and talked about how great the Aggies were.
And like there's an old joke they would tell, he sees a funeral as he's traveling along.
And he stops and gets out and goes over and stands there.
And the preacher says, well, does anybody have anything they'd like to say about the deceased?

nobody speaks up so pinky down says in that case could i say a few words about a m and i'm sure you've heard that that uh apocryphal tale before but i always thought he was sort of a joke quite frankly i mean you like uh and he made a really big deal about being this official greeter and his house which is right over on the corner of yeah it's right there where uh
Anyway, I know where it is.
But he had a sign out in the front yard, Pinky Downs, official breeder of A&M or something.
And I learned not long ago that he was a, then they called him directors, now we'd call it regent, in the 20s, in the early 1920s.
Is that right?
See, his family was in banking in Temple.
And I think during the Depression, I think the bank collapsed.
And I don't know whether it was mismanagement or what.
Did you, during your student days, did you ever see Earl Rudder in any way?
I'm sure I probably saw him at ceremonies and final review, you know.
What did you and the students think of him in those days?
I think everybody was pretty much afraid of him.
I think he was respected, you know.
What about Dean Hannigan, dean of students?
I don't think I had any encounters with Hannigan.
I got to know him when I was a faculty member.
He helped, you know, I got to know him when I first came here.
I started helping to get people to create the Aggie Sailing Club, get that started.
That's how I got to know him.
And then in 72, this is really interesting in itself, is that he asked me to be a chair of the Yell Eater and Bonfire Committee.
And I served from 72 to 76 as chair of that committee.
And this is the interesting part about it.
He was concerned about bonfire safety and a lot of the horseplay and the stuff that was going on and the drinking.
And he said, the problem I have, he said, we've had people that have been involved in my office that have chaired that committee.
And they get too close to these students and they let them get away with things.
And what I want is a faculty committee.
He asked me to recommend some other people to serve on it.
And I want a faculty committee that will have some independent oversight of these kids.
Well, I found out that was almost impossible.
to do.
But you know how I replaced the chair of the committee?
Who?
Malin Sutherland.
My, my.
And Malin wasn't a faculty member.
No, he was a staff member.
Yeah, yeah.
But that's why I say he went, Hannigan went from having a committee dominated by the MSC student programs office type people or the dean of students office to a faculty committee.
Do you know what Malin's, what the students nicknamed him, he was a tech officer, the nickname for him was the Slink.
Yeah, I can believe that.
That he slinked around.
But, you know, he's really kind of taken on the same role that Coldis had, which is that of a permissive parent.
And that's part of what went wrong with Bonfire.
And I'm amazed that he's going to be in charge of the committee to restructure it.
Anyway, but no, I thought I had a lot of respect for Hannigan.
He was a gruff, general type guy, but I think he knew the score on Bonfire and he knew there was a problem.
And what's really interesting, you know, what the problem
If you read that report, the red pot system is what was the corrupt influence in Bonfire.
Well, I resigned in 76 because Coldis would override the committee recommendations.
We'd make some recommendations about things about, one was the length of time they could work on it.
We tried to shorten the days you could work on it.
And it was concern about academic considerations and other things.
Coldis overrode us.
And that's when I resigned.
And I wrote him a letter.
I can't find it.
I threw it away.
or I gave it to maybe whoever left it with the Bonfire Committee records.

But I basically told him that the Red Pot system was corrupt, and that self-selection was going to get him in big trouble down the road, and that the Bonfire Committee ought to be the one that picked the Red Pot, the all-eaters.
Let's jump back.
I'm sorry.
No, no.
Did you jump work on Bonfire when you worked on Bonfire?
Oh, yeah.
Describe that.
Oh, that was a great time.
Where?
You go out in the woods and cut trees down.
Where was the cutting area?
I don't know.
Somewhere in Brazos County, but I couldn't begin to tell you.
And with what did you cut?
Well, we didn't cut anything.
Juniors and seniors cut.
Freshmen and sophomores picked logs up and carried them out of the woods and put them on trucks or laid them down.
And that's another thing is that freshmen and sophomores didn't work on the stack either.
And that was true when I was chair of that committee.
And half the people that were killed or injured were freshmen.
And about how long did y'all, did you work on?
Well, a couple of days.
That's all?
The two-day thing.
Yeah, it wasn't the length of time.
Well, you look at those pictures that are in the Bonfire Report.
It's not the gigantic, massive thing that it became, really, in the 60s.
Where was it held?
This thing behind Duncan.
It was already behind Duncan.
It was already behind Duncan.
A couple of days, and then, let's see, no, the Kennedy interruption comes after you're gone.
Yeah, that's the year I'm gone.
And let's see, other, I'm trying to think, oh, final review.
You must have gone through final review twice.
What were your recollections of that?
Well, it's an emotional thing, you know, particularly, you know, the ceremony of it, the seniors leaving, you know, and the new guys getting their boots on and marching around again.
So your second year, you're a junior who is not, do you know that you're not going to come back your senior year?
So you didn't put on any senior boots.
Did you go through the second?
Yeah, but I just didn't have boots
And no family and special people came down to watch or anything.
Did you go to commencements?
No, I don't think we did.
I don't recall ever going to a commencement.
I remember the commissioning ceremonies.
But they were generally held in conjunction with final review.
People were given their .
Were there any important speakers that you remember that came to the campus, whether it be for muster or commissioning or any?
If there were, I don't remember.
You don't remember?
No great celebrities?
No.
Did you go to muster?
Oh, yeah.
Where was it held?
As I recall, I think in the Grove.
What did you think about Muster?
I don't know that I had any great reflections of it at the time.
I don't think it was as big a deal then as it is now, at least not here.
I can't find it.
It's not filling up Reed Arena like it is now.
I haven't found many people that remember going to, knowing anything about Muster until World War II.
muster changes during World War II.
Is that right?
Immediately after.
Bonfire goes from being trash to being logs, so that society in many ways changed.
I'm not saying that's good or bad.
The first one where you really see where it's predominantly logs and you don't see the trash is the year they made the movie We've Never Been Licked.
I think that's right.
And they needed it as a backdrop.
You know, it plays a real prominent role when the Japanese students are breaking into the chemistry building, you know, to steal Pop Langer's secret formula for flexible steel.
You know, think about it.
Isn't that the corniest damn movie in the world?
Let's see.
Student indulgences.
We talked about alcohol.
What were students smoking then?
Well, no, there wasn't any drug smoking going on.
If there was, it may have been some of those Hispanic students from Mexico or South Texas that did it, but Lord, I mean, you could go to the state penitentiary for many years for smoking marijuana.
What did you and your, what lingo did you know relative to drugs when you were an undergraduate?
I don't, you know, there wasn't any, you know, drugs weren't a, I mean, hey, you could buy amphetamines.
We used to have amphetamines.
Had you heard the word heroin?
Oh, yeah.
You had?
Yeah.
Well, I remember seeing Reefer Madness in high school, you know, and just being scared to death.
And what, according to that movie, what happened to people who smoked marijuana?
They just absolutely went insane, jumped out of the windows and other things like that.

You know, I don't remember the movie having a real lot of impact, but I remember when I was in graduate school at Maryland, they used to show it as a camp film, and then people would go down and make fun of it and smoke marijuana.
That was later on, you know.
But when I was an undergraduate, you know, there...
I don't know of anybody that had marijuana or anything like that.
Had you ever seen marijuana?
No.
And certainly not heroin.
Smoking, what percentage you think of the undergraduates smoked then?
A large percentage smoked cigarettes.
What were the popular brands?
Winston, Paul Maul, Lucky Strikes, I guess, Camels.
If you were really, really macho, you smoked Camels, unfiltered Camels.
And cigars?
Some, but not much.
Pipes?
Yeah.
I think the pipes were kind of in a tent to be a little more sophisticated.
What about faculty members?
Did they smoke some?
I remember one guy in economics who smoked in class.
Who?
I don't recall his name.
I'm trying to remember.
He was in Nagel Hall.
Everybody in social science was, I guess, right?
I certainly remember faculty members who smoked in their offices, so that was certainly true.
Were there any campus celebrities at that time, any people, any student body?
There weren't any great athletes that everybody noticed in there or anything, were there?
No.
What about Aggie basketball?
Did you go to the games?
Did they play?
I don't remember ever going to the games.
You didn't go to G. Raleigh?
I don't remember.
Maybe I did.
I don't remember.
Because, see, it was packed.
I might have to, you know, as a virgin.
I don't like basketball.
I'm not a big basketball fan.
Right.
Now, we're getting near the end of the questions that I had thought of.
What have we left out that we should have covered?
We haven't so far.
I don't know.
We covered a lot.
A lot of things I never had thought about in years.
I can't think of anything.
I see.
Well, I should ask an obvious question.
Why did you not come back here your senior year?
Why did you go?
Well, part of it was that there was financial problems.
My parents felt that you weren't going to be a veterinarian.
That little place across the street was just fine.
And so there was no financial support to help from them.
Anyway.
And for what I wanted to do, it was probably a pretty good school.
And I had been there and knew people, so it wasn't like you were, I thought maybe at some point you might go back to A&M, but anyway.
In fact, when I came back as a faculty member, I never even considered it until my dissertation advisor invited me over to
her house and I met Bill Gibbons.
You remember Bill, the first chair?
He was a very impressive guy.
It had been pretty low on my list of places to go.
I hadn't thought about Bill Gibbons.
I don't know what happened to him.
I don't either.
So when you left, you weren't leaving to get away from A&M?
To some degree, yeah.
I think so.
I mean, some of the, it's sort of mixed feelings about it, you know.
There are aspects of it that, you know, there's always somebody harassing your butt, you know.
Admittedly, senior year, that wouldn't be as much.
It'd just be the military officers.
But, you know, and it's not a real, it wasn't a real pleasant place to be.
I mean, you know, there's all military, lots of marching.
No girls.
I mean, what more could a guy ask for, you know?
Now, your second year you had a car.
Yeah.
How often did you go back home?
Oh, just at, you know, Thanksgiving and Christmas.
And Easter?
Yeah.
Spring break?
We didn't have spring break.
We had Easter.
No, but, I mean, that's it.
That's about it.
How often did you go anywhere else out of Brazos County?
Well, except for going maybe a court trip or something, you didn't.
There wasn't much time.
